Basic Dplyr

The dplyr package uses verbs to perform data manipulation.

  • filter() and slice()
  • arrange()
  • select() and rename()
  • distinct()
  • mutate() and transmute()
  • sample_n() and sample_frac()

Overall Questions

  1. Split the complete dataset into individual planes and then summarise each plane by counting the number of flights (count = n()) and computing the average distance and arrival delay . Then plot this:
ggplot(delay, aes(dist, delay)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = count), alpha = 1/2) +
  geom_smooth() +
  scale_size_area()
#The group_by function can be used to split the dataset into individual planes (which are distinguished by their tail number). After the planes are grouped, the summarise function can count the number of flights for each plane and their average distance and arrival delay (again the NA's are removed).
delay <- flights %>% 
  group_by(tail_num) %>%
    summarise(count = n(), dist = mean(distance[!is.na(distance)]), delay = mean(arr_delay[!is.na(arr_delay)]))

ggplot(delay, aes(dist, delay)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = count), alpha = 1/2) +
  geom_smooth() +
  scale_size_area()

#Each individual plane is represented as a dot on the graph, with its average distance travelled plotted against its average delay in arrival. The size of the dot gives an idea of how many flights the plane has made, with a key to the sizes given on the graph.
  1. Find the number of planes and the number of flights that go to each possible destination.
#First, you have to group by the destination of the flights. Then, to summarise - first the number of planes is equal to the number of distinct tail numbers that go to a particular destination, this can be obtained with the n_distinct function. Finally, the number of flights is just equal to the number of observations for each destination, which can be obtained with the n() function.
flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
    summarise(num_planes = n_distinct(tail_num), num_flights = n())

More Difficult

In the videos we learned about piping our commands. The goal of piping is to help use with the flow of our analysis. The steps we take are: - Think about it. - Describe it. - Do it.

  1. Consider the code Below:
filter(
  summarise(
    select(
      group_by(flights, year, month, day),
      arr_delay, dep_delay
    ),
    arr = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    dep = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ),
  arr > 30 | dep > 30
)
  1. What are some problems with this function?

Its not clear what order the functions are being called in. It seems like the filter function is being called first, but in fact it is the last function that is applied. Its not clear what is intended to be done, so it could use some comments.

  1. How easy is it to follow the logic of this?

Its difficult, since it is not clear what the arguments for the filter, summarise, select functions are, since they are on different lines from the original call. Its not immediately clear what the data set that is being operated on is, since the flights tbl is not mentioned until the functions have all been declared. The piping will immediately declare the data set being worked on, and the functions will be applied in a more intuitive order.

  1. Rewrite this using piping to make it more understandable.
#This is the above function rewritten with piping. After each function is called, what it does will be described.
flights %>%
  
  group_by(year, month, day) %>% #This groups the flights by their date.
  
    select(arr_delay, dep_delay) %>% #The columns of arrival delay and departure delay are selected.
  
      summarise(arr = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), dep = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% #The average arrival delay and departure delay for each day are given by the summarise function, with NA entries removed.
  
        filter(arr > 30 | dep > 30) #Only the days where the arrival arrival delay or departure delay is greater than 30 are included.

#Check to see the functions produce the same results.
version1 <- filter(
  summarise(
    select(
      group_by(flights, year, month, day),
      arr_delay, dep_delay
    ),
    arr = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    dep = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ),
  arr > 30 | dep > 30
)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `year`, `month`, `day`
version2 <- flights %>%
  group_by(year, month, day) %>% 
    select(arr_delay, dep_delay) %>% 
      summarise(arr = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE), dep = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
        filter(arr > 30 | dep > 30)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `year`, `month`, `day`
all.equal(version1, version2)
## [1] TRUE
#The all.equal function confirms that version1 and version2 both give the same table.
  1. Consider the code below
hourly_delay <- filter(
  summarise(
    group_by(
      filter(
        flights, 
        !is.na(dep_delay)
      ),
      date, hour
    ),
    delay=mean(dep_delay),
    n=n()
  ),
  n>10
)
  1. What are some problems with this function?

The difficulties are the same as the previous function - its not clear which order the functions are called in. We know that the new table is supposed to denote hourly delay, but it is not immediately clear how that is calculated. There is another more serious problem, which is that the function throws an error because there is no date column in the flights data set - this new column must first be created with the mutate function.

  1. How easy is it to follow the logic of this?

The same problems as in the previous function, the arguments to the functions are not on the same line, the functions are written in a way that is not intuitive, its not obvious what data set is being worked on. The piping will help to clear this up.

  1. Rewrite this using piping to make it more understandable.
#This is the above function rewritten with piping. After each function is called, what it does will be described.

hourly_delay <- flights %>% 
  
  mutate(date = as.Date(with(flights, paste(year, month, day,sep="-")), "%Y-%m-%d")) %>% #The mutate function adds a column that gives the date of each flight, using the three separate columns for year, month and day. This is not done in the original version of this function.
  
    filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>% #The observations where the departure delay is NA are filtered out.
      
        group_by(date, hour) %>% #Then the flights are grouped by date (which is now a column) and hour.
  
          summarise(delay = mean(dep_delay), n = n()) %>% #Then the average delay is given for each flight every hour of every day, along with the number of flights that hour. 
  
            filter(n > 10) #Finally, only the hours where there were at least 10 flights are included.

#To sum up: the function tells you, for every hour of every day recorded, the average departure delay and number of flights in that hour, as long as more than 10 flights left that hour.

Background

With this in class project our goal will be to work further with dplyr in order to analyze some questions that are relevant. We will begin with a dataset from the Global Terrorism Database. We will also try and repeat some of the basic analysis performed on this in a fivethirtyeight article. Our goal will be to reproduce what they have in there and then also ask some questions we might have that they possibly ignored. Think about if they actually analyzed what the article was about.

This database has been a popular database used in data science and machine learning competitions.

The Data

You will need the following resources to best help you with this:

  • The Code Chunk Below Loads the Code

In the above code chunk:

  1. What does eval=F mean?

Incuding eval = F in the r call in the R Markdown file will make so the code included in the call is not executed. The code is still displayed.

  1. What does echo=F mean?

Including echo=F in the r call makes it so the code is not displayed when the R Markdown file is knitted.

  1. What does cache=T mean?

Adding cache=T saves an image of the r code included in the r call, so it does not have to be rerun each time the R Markdown file is knitted.

  1. What might some implications of combining them and then analyzing the data?

To combine these two datasets, the columns of the terror_93 set must be matched with columns of the terror set. However, a lot of these columns do not have exact matches. The next question will go over the details of one way to join the data sets, so that for each year and country all of the variables that appear in terror_93 are represented.

  1. For this part join these datasets together, keeping only the variables in the 1993 data. Call this terrorp_93. Note you will need to rename columns in 1993 so they match up.
#The terrorp_93 table contains the information from the terror.csv documents, grouping by year and country, and adding the total number of people killed and wounded in that year and country, as well as the number of people killed and wounded from the US in that year and country.
library(dplyr)

terrorp_93 <- terror %>% 
  group_by(iyear, country_txt) %>% 
    summarise(No.Of.Incidents = n(), Number.Killed    =sum(nkill[!is.na(nkill)]), Number.US.Killed = sum(nkillus[!is.na(nkillus)]), Number.Injured = sum(nwound[!is.na(nwound)]), Number.Injured.US = sum(nwoundus[!is.na(nwoundus)]))

#This data table gives the total number of terrorist incidents each year.
incidents_per_year <- terrorp_93 %>% 
  group_by(iyear) %>% 
    summarise(incidents_year = sum(No.Of.Incidents))

#The incidents_per_year column is joined with the terrorp_93 data frame to give the number of attacks each year. Then the percentage of attacks committed in each country per year is calculated.

terrorp_93 <- left_join(terrorp_93, incidents_per_year, by = "iyear")

terrorp_93 <- mutate(terrorp_93, percent = paste(round(No.Of.Incidents/incidents_year * 100, digits = 2), "%", sep = ""))

#Rename the columns of terrorp_93 to match terror_93, add year column to terror_93.
terror_93$iyear <- 1993

terrorp_93 <- rename(terrorp_93, Country = country_txt, Number.of.Incidents = No.Of.Incidents, Percent = percent, Number.US.Injured = Number.Injured.US)

#Now join the two data frames.
Terror_Summarised <- full_join(terrorp_93, terror_93)

France Only

  1. Find the number of incidents per year and order them by year.
#The number of incidents column is selected from the France table, and then it is arranged by year.
French_Incidents <- France %>%
  select(year, Number.of.Incidents) %>%
    arrange(year)
  1. Find the number of fatalities by year and call this data fratFatByYear,name the count of fatalities to be fatalities.
#There is already a column for Number.Killed in the France data, so we need only select that column as well as the year column, then rename Number.Killed to fatalities.
fraFatByYear <- France %>%
  select(year, Number.Killed) %>%
    rename(fatalities = Number.Killed)
  1. Plot this:
g <- ggplot(data=fraFatByYear, aes(x=year, y=fatalities))+
  geom_line() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Fatalities")+
  ggtitle("Fatalities from terrorism, in France")
g

  1. How does this compare to what the article has?

The plot looks pretty similar to the one for the article - however, the article was written in the wake of the 2015 Paris terrorist attacks, which accounts for the large spike in our plot that is not there on the fivethirtyeight plot.

ALL EU

  1. Consider EU Countries only since 1986. Save this shortened data as euData_since1986.
#To do this, just filter euCountries for year greater than or equal to 1986.
euData_since1986 <- euCountries %>%
    filter(year >= 1986)
  1. Tally EU-wide fatalities by year. Call the count of fatalities, fatalities, call this data euFatalities.
#This table is generated by grouping by year, then summarising with a new column fatalities that sums the fatalities in each of the EU countries that year.
euFatalities <- euData_since1986 %>%
    group_by(year) %>%
      summarise(fatalities = sum(Number.Killed))
  1. Plot this:
g2 <- ggplot(data=euFatalities, aes(x=year, y=fatalities))+
  geom_line() + xlab("Year") + ylab("Fatalities")+
  ggtitle("Fatalities from terrorism, in EU countries since 1986 \n Of members who joined in 1986 or before")
g2

#This plot largely matches the fivethirtyeight plot for EU terrorism after 1986. You can see the effect of particularly disastrous terrorist events, like the Lockerbie bombing in 1988 and the Madrid Bus Bombings in 2004 as well as the more recent spike of terrorism.

Country-by-Country Breakdown

  1. Keep only the following variables:
    • iyear
    • country_txt
    • nkill Call this data euData.
#The columns have different names, but these are the same variables. This table will have the year, Country and the number of people killed in terrorist incidents in that country that year.
euData <- euData_since1986 %>%
  select(year, Country, Number.Killed)
  1. Count the number of Fatalities by country.
#The euData table is grouped by Country, and then summarised with a new column fatalities equal to the sum of the fatalities in each year. The resulting table has the number of fatalities in each EU country since 1986.
euFatalities_by_Country <- euData %>%
    group_by(Country) %>%
      summarise(fatalities = sum(Number.Killed))
